text: The Science Fiction Radio Show A commentary on science fiction today Presented by the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association This is David Cruz Daryl Lane And David Carson The subject of this show is science fiction music, including that of science fiction motion pictures and other sources. The importance of music to movies, I think, is an obvious thing. A good musical score can do a number of things for a movie. It can create a mood for the entire picture. It can dramatize the actions of a particular scene. It can also rouse the emotions of the audience. With science fiction movies, I think this is true also, but with another dimension to it. The situations and moods of a science fiction movie might be of a very different nature. You might have, for instance, a meeting with a race of aliens. The awesomeness of a space battle. The discovery of a new planet. Situations or moods that might take something a little different, a little special. And I think it requires a special breed of composer to accomplish this. But the best science fiction music, I think, can evoke what good science fiction itself evokes, a sense of wonder and excitement. Yeah. . ¶¶ ¶¶ That was the main theme from Star Wars. Much of the music used in science fiction movies has its roots in classical music. One of the more popular and well-known works of this type is the suite for large orchestra by Gustav Holst called The Planets. It was written between 1914 and 1918. And it contains a series of pieces on each planet that was known at that time, Mars through Neptune, and gives a musical impression of each one. During the filming of Star Wars, they used the music from Holst's The Planets to use as background music behind the scenes while they were being roughly edited together. They used this music in order to give the director and crew a sense of what the music was going to be like when the picture was completed. They liked the music so much that when they had the original score written, they had it written with the same type of orchestration and theme that was in The Planets. As an example now of what this is like, and maybe you could compare it to what the Star Wars theme was like, let's listen to Mars, The Bringer of War, from Gustav Holst's The Planets. This is Bernard Ehrman conducting the London Philharmonic Orchestra. The Planets The Planets The Planets The Planets The Planets The Planets The Planets The Planets The Planets The Planets The Planets The Planets there. They're more like tone poems that evoke particular moods. For instance, Mars, the bringer of war, evokes the mechanized horrors of modern warfare, since in his astrological aspect, Mars is the god of war. Indeed, as Harry Halbrack said, the planets belongs to our time as genuine space music. And of course, who can forget the unique blend of classical music with science fiction and probably one of the greatest science fiction movies of all time, 2001. So, so, so, so, so, so, so, so, so, so, so, just as in Star Wars, the people producing 2001 used classical music behind their movie as they were editing it together. The difference here is being that they liked the music so much that they used it in the movie. And what they had to do was to, to junk an entire score that had been composed by Alex North. And it was not used in the movie because this, this classical background was so successful. The piece you just heard, which is probably the most famous theme from the movie 2001, is in actuality a piece from a classical composition called Alsosprak Zarathustra, written by Richard Strauss in 1896. It's from a long tone poem. This is just the fanfare from that piece. Another piece used in the film was written by Richard's father, Johan, and it is one of the most famous of the Viennese waltzes, the Blue Danube, used in the incredible, the and unforgettable scene of the rocket ship approaching the space station in Earth orbit. As the 1950s began, we were treated to a number of low budget science fiction films. One of them in particular, Rocket Ship XM, had music by a rather well known classical composer, Frodo Grofe, the composer of the Grand Canyon Suite. Grofe was noted for his suites. He wrote many of them. His musical method was very simple. If you want to evoke the sound of a gun, you would fire a gun, which he did in his, one of his compositions. If you wanted the sound of a fire engine, you would record a fire engine. So his music is full of old typewriters clacking, earthquakes going off, fog horns bellowing, cable car bells ringing. And that kind of simple basic method, I think, is appropriate, particularly appropriate for the, for a dramatic science fiction movie, which Rocket Ship XM was. In 1950, producer Robert Lippert decided to approach Grofe and try to get him to compose the music for the film. Grofe did not particularly want to be involved with low budget science fiction films, which were not exactly considered the best by critics at that time. And he agreed only to write the basic themes for the music. The actual composition of the orchestration was done by Albert Glasser.
